and their history and beliefs and everything else, if you're not interacting with anyone else, what is the point?<br><br>&quot;Does the server rules actually limit people's ability to interact in an IN-character fashion?&quot;<br><br>The rules limit people's ability to interact in ANY fashion, in or out of character.<br><br>&quot;Does the server rules affects how a good aligned should react to an evil aligned?&quot;<br><br>Well, to a certain extent, yes.  Suppose a good aligned cleric of Nife wants to heal the wounds of an evil warrior of Zek, because she believes it is her duty to heal all wounds, but she can't because of alignment?  Some say this is enforcing roleplaying because a good aligned character shouldn't want to assist an evil aligned character; others say it's limiting roleplay by forcing characters to behave in a certain faction.  I don't have as much of a problem with the alignment rules as I do some of the others.<br><br>&quot;Does the server rules demand how a dwarf should react at the sight of an ogre (taking into their racial history in consideration)?&quot;<br><br>Actually?  If the dwarf were stronger, he'd probably kill the ogre.  But unless the ogre agrees to a duel, he couldn't do that here.  About the only way he could react that the ogre would understand, would be /rude<br> <br>&quot;All the answers are NO. It is the P-E-O-P-L-E that is responsible for that part, not the server rules.&quot;<br><br>True... my main complaint is that the server rules foster isolation, which isn't conducive to roleplay.<br><br>-Giò<br> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=morgrist>Morgrist</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 97<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(12/6/01 12:42:39 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFr